Texts.Reference: Welcome to the application. This is a demo application built to present abp.io platform's commercial modules. You can see the list of modules on https://commercial.abp.io/modules. Each module on that list consists of NuGet and NPM packages. This application only uses those modules via NuGet and NPM packages. For more information visit abp.io.

The entity is a model that represents a database record and this is the name of the entity. It should be in PascalCase. It must start with a letter and can contain only letters and numbers [A-z][0-9]. Eg: Book, BookStore.
Plural name of the entity will be used in collection names, folder names. Eg: Books, BookStores
For relational databases it will be used as table name, for NoSQL databases it will be used as collection name. Eg: Books, BookStores.
It will be the namespace of the C# classes. Use PascalCase for namespaces, no underscore and seperate logical components with periods. Don't use multiple namespace (Eg: "Library.Books")
This is the base (parent) class of your entity that will be derived from an ABP Framework class.

Primary key serves as a unique identifier for each entity instance in database. It will be used as entity's primary key data type. Guid is recommended!

Property name should be in PascalCase. It must start with a letter and can contain only letters and numbers [A-z][0-9]. Do not use Get and Set as prefixes and no underscores with property name. Avoid abbreviations. Eg: PageCount

You can set your own connection string if you don`t want to use the default one. As the default database provider is SQL Server, you can only enter connection string for SQL Server!
Specifies the template type. "Application Template" generates a web application. "Module Template" generates a reusable application module.

Your project name is your solution name. Common convention is using as Organization.ProjectName. Eg: `Acme.BookStore`. However, you can also use single-level namespacing like `BookStore` or three-level namespacing like `Acme.Retail.BookStore`.
The directory where the project will be created.
Creates a new folder in the output folder. If checked, the project will be in a new folder in the output folder, if unchecked project will be generated directly in the output folder
Specifies the front-end framework. You can choose MVC (with jQuery) or Angular (latest).
Specifies the mobile application type. The mobile app is a simple application which is connected to the backend of the web project. If you do not need a mobile app you can choose 'None'
Specifies the database provider. Available options are Entity Framework Core and MongoDB.
Creates a tiered solution where Web and HTTP API layers are physically separated. If you don't check this option, it creates a layered solution which is less complex and suitable for most scenarios.
Specifies to not include the UI. This makes possible to create service-only modules (a.k.a. microservices - without UI).
Uses latest pre-release version, if there is at least one pre-release after latest stable version.
Separates the Identity Server application from the API host application. If not specified, you will have a single endpoint in the server-side.
